page.text: SR 369 (Matt Highway) / Gravitt Road / Main Site Driveway
The study intersection is SR 369 at Gravitt Road, which is located approximately 0.86 miles
west of the intersection of SR 369 (Matt Highway) / SR 9 (Dahlonega Highway) in Forsyth
County, Georgia. A retail/office development is proposed to the north of the study intersection
and the Main Site Driveway of the development will line up with Gravitt Road, adding a north
leg (southbound approach) to the intersection. A school bus driveway located to the east is
proposed to be realigned with the Main Site Driveway allowing school buses to use the new
roadway through the proposed development and the proposed traffic signal. A location map is
The study intersection is in Forsyth County.
Forsyth County requested this traffic engineering study.
The purpose of this study is to determine if the intersection of SR 369 / Gravitt Road / Main Site
Driveway will warrant installation of a traffic signal after the addition of traffic volumes that will
be generated by the proposed development.
SR 369 (Matt Highway) is currently a two-lane east-west undivided roadway in the vicinity of
the site. SR 369 has shoulder and ditch section on either side of road for drainage.
The intersection of SR 369 / Gravitt Road is currently a three-legged unsignalized intersection.
The intersection is stop-controlled for the Gravitt Road (northbound) with SR 369 (eastbound
Existing turning movement and 24-hour approach counts were collected near the intersection of
SR 369 / Gravitt Road and SR 369 / School Driveway on Tuesday, April 10, 2007. The counts at
the study intersection revealed traffic volumes of 8,369 vehicles per day for the eastbound
approach, 9,060 vehicles per day for the westbound approach along SR 369, 922 vehicles per
day for the northbound approach along Gravitt Road and 807 vehicles per day for southbound
approach along School Driveway. These counts are attached in the Appendix.
The posted speed limit on SR 369 is 45 mph. Gravitt Road has a posted speed limit of 35 mph.
No evidence of any significant pedestrian activity was observed along SR 369 or Gravitt Road in
the vicinity of the study intersection.
Existing intersection delay was calculated using existing AM and PM peak hour volumes and
Synchro software. The results of the delay analysis reveal that the westbound left turn movement
along SR 369 has a delay of 9.3 seconds/vehicle during the AM peak hour and a delay of 13.7
seconds/vehicle during the PM peak hour. The northbound approach along Gravitt Road has a
delay of 23.8 seconds/vehicle during the AM Peak hour and 37.3 seconds/vehicle during the PM
peak hour. Based on these delays the northbound approach is operating at LOS E during the
No parking is allowed on SR 369 or Gravitt Road in the vicinity of the study intersection.
Accident data obtained from Georgia DOT revealed that seven accidents occurred in the year
2004 while nine accidents occurred in the year 2005. Three out of the nine accidents that
occurred in the year 2005 were angle type collision. Accident history is included in the appendix.
There is presently only one signalized intersection within one mile of the study intersection. It is
the intersection of SR 369 (Matt Highway) / SR 9 (Dahlonega Highway) which is located
approximately 0.86 mile east of the study intersection. A figure showing the signalized
intersection is included in the Appendix (Figure 2).
The sight distance looking east from proposed Main Site Driveway is approximately 1700 feet
while looking west is approximately1300 feet. The sight distances looking east and west from
the Gravitt Road / Main Site Driveway intersection will be sufficient to allow left and right
turners to safely enter and exit SR 369 from the Gravitt Road / Main Site Driveway intersection
The posted speed limit on SR 369 is 45 mph. A signal warrant analysis was performed using a
main street approach speed of 45 mph with the intersection geometry of a single-lane main street
and a single-lane side street. To be conservative, a northbound and a southbound right-turn
reduction of 100% were applied for the side streets to account for any right turners that may
arrive at the intersection and turn right without waiting for a gap in the eastbound and westbound
Per the request of the GDOT General Office, when the speed limit on the main road is 40 mph or
higher, signal warrants are to be evaluated using both the 70% option as allowed by MUTCD
when the speed limit is 40 mph or greater and also the 100% option that is typically used for
speeds below 40 mph. The total 24-hour site generated traffic volumes and the existing traffic
volumes on SR 369 were used in the signal warrant analyses. It was found that one of the
vehicular volume warrants (Warrant 3 – Peak Hour Volume) would be satisfied for the 100%

The proposed development will consist of 27,000 sq. ft. of retail space and 13,200 sq.ft. of office
space. A site plan for the development is included in the appendix (Figure 3). Trip generation
estimates for the project were based on the rates and equations published in the 7th edition of the
Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) Trip Generation report. The trip generation was
based on the following ITE Land Uses: 820 – Shopping Center and 710 – General Office. The
traffic volumes generated by the proposed development are shown in Table 1.
Enter Exit Total Enter Exit Total 2-way
For trip assignment purposes, it was estimated that 40% of the site-related traffic will come from
SR 369 east, 50% would come from SR 369 west and 10% would come from Gravitt Road.
In future, the existing intersection of SR 369 / School Driveway located to the east of study
intersection will be realigned with the Main Site Driveway (Proposed Road) of the study
intersection. These diverted trips were also considered in our study. Future capacity analysis was
performed for both a signalized and an unsignalized condition for the study intersection. Future
intersection operations analyses results for the intersection of SR 369 / Gravitt Road / Main Site
Driveway are shown in Tables 2 and 3, respectively. The methodology used for evaluating traffic
operations at the intersection is based on the criteria set forth in the Transportation Research
Board’s 2000 update of the Highway Capacity Manual (HCM). Synchro Software (HCS), which
emulates the HCM methodology, was used for conducting the analysis.
As shown in Table 2, the northbound and southbound approaches at the intersection of SR 369 /
Gravitt Road / Main Site Driveway will experience excessive delays during both the AM and
PM peak hours without the installation of a traffic signal. Following the installation of a traffic
signal as shown in Table 3, the intersection will operate at LOS A during the AM peak hour and
at LOS C during the PM peak hour.
A left turn phase analysis was conducted at the study intersection to analyze if any left turn
movement will meet the criteria for a protected left turn phasing using product rule for the AM
and PM peak hours. The results of the analysis revealed that the eastbound and westbound left
turn movement will require protected-permissive signal phasing for the future traffic volumes.
Figures 4 and 5 in appendix show the results of the analysis.

The results of the signal warrant analysis indicate that the traffic volumes at the intersection of
SR 369 / Gravitt Road / Main Site Driveway will meet the MUTCD warrants for installation of a
traffic signal after completion of the proposed retail/office development and realignment of
school bus driveway. Therefore, installation of a traffic signal at this location is recommended. It
is also recommended that the eastbound and westbound left turn movements have protected-
permissive signal phases. In addition, it is also recommended that dedicated eastbound left turn
and westbound right turn lanes be added on SR 369 as per Georgia DOT standards for traffic
entering the site. It is further recommended that a separate left and a shared through / right turn
lanes be installed on the side street (Main Site driveway). It is also recommended that the
northbound approach to the intersection have a separate left and a shared through / right turn
